## 3. Canonical Skill Creation

**All new skills are created in the canonical NGOSkills repo** so they auto-propagate to both Cursor and Claude via the existing symlink architecture.

### Where new skills go

| Skill type | Canonical location | Triggered when |
|---|---|---|
| Salesforce / nonprofit / domain skill | `~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills/skills/<name>/` | User asks for a new `sf-*` skill, domain skill, or anything that fits the NGOSkills scope |
| Cursor-ecosystem skill (workflows, tooling, meta) | `~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills/skills-cursor/<name>/` | User asks for a new dev-workflow skill that isn't Salesforce-specific |
| Truly project-local, never reused | `<project>/.cursor/skills/<name>/` | Rare. Confirm with user before choosing this path |

**Never create a new skill directly in `~/.cursor/skills/` or `~/.claude/skills/`.** Those directories contain symlinks to canonical or built-ins. Direct creation there breaks the auto-sync model and will be flagged as drift by `sync-skills.sh`.

### After creating a skill

Always run, in this exact order:

1. `~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills/scripts/sync-skills.sh --fix` — creates the per-skill symlink in `~/.cursor/skills/<name>` (Claude picks it up automatically through the directory-level symlink at `~/.claude/skills`)
2. `~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills/scripts/sync-skills.sh --check` — confirms drift=0
3. (if the user is ready) `git add . && git commit` inside `~/Cursor/Skills/NGOSkills` — never auto-push without explicit user approval

### SKILL.md requirements

Every new SKILL.md MUST have YAML frontmatter with:

```yaml
---
name: <skill-name>
description: >
  One-sentence summary.
  TRIGGER when: <plain-text scenarios that should activate this skill>
  DO NOT TRIGGER when: <scenarios that look related but should route elsewhere, with the alternative skill named in parentheses>
---
```

The `TRIGGER when:` / `DO NOT TRIGGER when:` clauses are what both Cursor and Claude semantically match against the user's plain-text prompts. A skill without them will not be auto-routed and will only activate when the user names it explicitly. Treat missing triggers as an authoring bug.

